
[1]rigor

   RIG'OR, n. [L. from rigeo, to be stiff.

   1. Stiffness; rigidness; as Gorgonian rigor.

   2. In medicine, a sense of chilliness, with contradiction of the skin;
   a convulsive shuddering or slight tremor, as in the cold fit of a
   fever.

   3. Stiffness of opinion or temper; severity; sternness.

   All his rigor is turned to grief and pity.

   4. Severity of life; austerity; voluntary submission to pain,
   abstinence or mortification.

   5. Strictness; exactness without allowance, latitude or indulgence; as
   the rigor of criticism; to execute a law with rigor; to enforce moral
   duties with rigor.

   6. violence; fury. [Not in use.]

   7. Hardness; solidity. [Unusual.]

   8. Severity; asperity; as the rigors of a cold winter.
